{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501658"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:31:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:31:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1775"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1775"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.62,0.17,0.06,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108252"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42396"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108252"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following an unconscious collapse at work. She has been unwell for the past two days with a diarrhoeal illness. She has a medical history of severe asthma and takes long-term low-dose prednisolone 10 mg daily. Her other regular medications are salbutamol, budesonide/formoterol and mepolizumab (last taken two weeks ago). She is a non-smoker and has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 80/30 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is an occasional wheeze on chest auscultation. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. Abdominal examination is normal. Her blood glucose level is 3.0 mmol/L (3.6-5.4). Intravenous fluid therapy is commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ketoconazole infusion","Intravenous hydrocortisone","Adrenaline infusion","Oral prednisolone","Salbutamol nebulisers"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with an adrenal crisis due to long-term adrenal suppression from prednisolone use. The most important next step in management is administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E. Adrenal crisis is an acute, life-threatening event in patients with adrenal insufficiency, and immediate treatment with parenteral glucocorticoids is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient in this acute situation. In an adrenal crisis, parenteral administration is necessary to ensure rapid absorption and action of the glucocorticoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol nebulisers\u003C/strong\u003E might help with the patient\u0027s asthma but would not address the underlying adrenal crisis, which is the more urgent concern given the patient\u0027s hypotension and altered consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not the first-line treatment for adrenal crisis. While it might temporarily improve blood pressure, it doesn\u0027t address the underlying cortisol deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetoconazole infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this situation. Ketoconazole is sometimes used to treat Cushing\u0027s syndrome by inhibiting cortisol production, which would be counterproductive in a patient with suspected adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdrenal crisis often presents with non-specific signs and symptoms, and is frequently precipitated by infections or other stressors. In this case, the patient\u0027s recent diarrhoeal illness likely triggered the crisis. The incidence of adrenal crisis is estimated to be eight per 100 patient-years among those with adrenal insufficiency. Long-term management should focus on patient education about stress dosing during illness or physiological stress, and the necessity of parenteral hydrocortisone therapy in emergencies. Patients should carry or wear a medical alert bracelet indicating steroid dependency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intravenous hydrocortisone should be the first step in the management of a patient with an adrenal crisis.","Adrenal crisis is a life-threatening condition often precipitated by infection or stress in patients with adrenal insufficiency.","Patients on long-term corticosteroid therapy are at risk of adrenal suppression and crisis when faced with physiological stress."],"references":["Dineen R, Thompson CJ, Sherlock M. Adrenal crisis: prevention and management in adult patients. Ther Adv Endocrinol Metab. 2019;10:2042018819848218-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T19:21:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T19:23:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108252"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/183"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Addison\u0027s disease","synonyms":["Hypoadrenalism","Primary adrenal insufficiency","Hypoaldosteronism"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40